# ---- AMBIGUOUS (question itself is underspecified) ----
{"id": "ambiguous-001", "question": "How do I scale?", "golden_answer": "The question is ambiguous — Kubernetes supports scaling at multiple levels: scaling Pods within a Deployment (kubectl scale or HorizontalPodAutoscaler), scaling nodes via the Cluster Autoscaler, or scaling individual container resources via VerticalPodAutoscaler. The system should ask which kind of scaling is intended before answering.", "expected_source_files": [], "type": "ambiguous"}
{"id": "ambiguous-002", "question": "What's the best way to deploy?", "golden_answer": "The question is ambiguous — 'best' depends on context. For stateless apps, a Deployment is standard; for stateful workloads, a StatefulSet; for daemons that run on every node, a DaemonSet; for one-off batch work, a Job or CronJob. The system should ask what kind of workload before recommending an approach.", "expected_source_files": [], "type": "ambiguous"}
{"id": "ambiguous-003", "question": "How do I make my cluster faster?", "golden_answer": "The question is ambiguous — 'faster' could refer to API server latency, scheduling throughput, network throughput, application response time, or build/deploy turnaround. Each has different optimization techniques. The system should ask which dimension of performance is the concern.", "expected_source_files": [], "type": "ambiguous"}

# ---- LOOKUP (second batch) ----
{"id": "lookup-013", "question": "What is a Namespace in Kubernetes?", "golden_answer": "A Namespace is a mechanism for isolating groups of resources within a single cluster. Resource names must be unique within a Namespace but not across Namespaces (this applies to namespaced objects like Deployments and Services, not to cluster-wide objects like Nodes and StorageClasses). Namespaces are intended for environments with many users spread across multiple teams or projects.", "expected_source_files": ["content/en/docs/concepts/overview/working-with-objects/namespaces.md"], "type": "lookup"}
{"id": "lookup-014", "question": "What is the difference between a liveness probe and a readiness probe?", "golden_answer": "A liveness probe determines whether a container is still running; if it fails, the kubelet restarts the container. A readiness probe determines whether a container is ready to serve traffic; if it fails, the Pod is removed from Service endpoints but the container is not restarted. They solve different problems: liveness recovers from deadlocks, readiness handles temporary unavailability.", "expected_source_files": ["content/en/docs/tasks/configure-pod-container/configure-liveness-readiness-startup-probes.md"], "type": "lookup"}
{"id": "lookup-015", "question": "What is a StatefulSet?", "golden_answer": "A StatefulSet is a workload API object that manages stateful applications. Unlike a Deployment, it gives each Pod a stable, unique identity (a persistent hostname and ordinal index) and stable persistent storage. Pods are created, scaled, and deleted in a strictly ordered, predictable way.", "expected_source_files": ["content/en/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/statefulset.md"], "type": "lookup"}
{"id": "lookup-016", "question": "What is a DaemonSet?", "golden_answer": "A DaemonSet ensures that a copy of a specified Pod runs on every (or selected) node in the cluster. As nodes are added to the cluster, the DaemonSet automatically adds Pods to them. Typical uses are running cluster-storage daemons, logs-collection daemons, and node-monitoring agents.", "expected_source_files": ["content/en/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/daemonset.md"], "type": "lookup"}
{"id": "lookup-017", "question": "What is a Job in Kubernetes?", "golden_answer": "A Job creates one or more Pods and ensures that a specified number of them successfully complete. When the specified number of completions is reached, the Job is complete. The Job retries by creating new Pods if any of the Pods fail or are deleted, until the desired number of successful completions is reached.", "expected_source_files": ["content/en/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/job.md"], "type": "lookup"}
{"id": "lookup-018", "question": "What is a Node in Kubernetes?", "golden_answer": "A Node is a worker machine in Kubernetes — either a virtual or physical machine — that runs Pods. Each Node contains the services necessary to run Pods (the kubelet, container runtime, and kube-proxy) and is managed by the control plane.", "expected_source_files": ["content/en/docs/concepts/architecture/nodes.md"], "type": "lookup"}
{"id": "lookup-019", "question": "What does the kubelet do?", "golden_answer": "The kubelet is an agent that runs on every Node. It takes PodSpecs that describe the Pods that should run, and ensures those Pods and their containers are running and healthy. It communicates with the container runtime to start, stop, and monitor containers.", "expected_source_files": ["content/en/docs/concepts/overview/components.md"], "type": "lookup"}
{"id": "lookup-020", "question": "What is etcd in Kubernetes?", "golden_answer": "etcd is a consistent and highly-available key-value store used by Kubernetes as the backing store for all cluster data. It stores the entire state of the cluster — every Pod, Service, ConfigMap, Secret, and other resource. The API server is the only component that talks to etcd directly.", "expected_source_files": ["content/en/docs/concepts/overview/components.md"], "type": "lookup"}
{"id": "lookup-021", "question": "What does the kube-controller-manager do?", "golden_answer": "The kube-controller-manager runs the controllers that watch the cluster state via the API server and drive it toward the desired state. Built-in controllers include the Node controller, ReplicaSet controller, Endpoints controller, and ServiceAccount controller. Logically they are separate controllers, but they are compiled into one binary.", "expected_source_files": ["content/en/docs/concepts/overview/components.md"], "type": "lookup"}
{"id": "lookup-022", "question": "What is a taint and a toleration in Kubernetes?", "golden_answer": "A taint is applied to a Node to repel certain Pods. A toleration is applied to a Pod to allow it to be scheduled on a Node with a matching taint. Taints and tolerations work together to ensure that Pods are not scheduled onto inappropriate Nodes — the Node taints repel, and matching Pod tolerations permit scheduling (though they do not guarantee it, since other scheduling criteria still apply).", "expected_source_files": ["content/en/docs/concepts/scheduling-eviction/taint-and-toleration.md"], "type": "lookup"}
{"id": "lookup-023", "question": "What is an init container?", "golden_answer": "An init container is a specialized container that runs to completion before the app containers in a Pod start. A Pod can have multiple init containers, which run sequentially. Init containers are typically used to perform setup tasks like waiting for a service to be available, fetching configuration, or running migrations.", "expected_source_files": ["content/en/docs/concepts/workloads/pods/init-containers.md"], "type": "lookup"}
{"id": "lookup-024", "question": "What is a CronJob in Kubernetes?", "golden_answer": "A CronJob creates Jobs on a repeating schedule, written in Cron format. It is useful for running periodic tasks like backups, report generation, or scheduled cleanup. The CronJob controller creates a Job for each scheduled execution.", "expected_source_files": ["content/en/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/cron-jobs.md"], "type": "lookup"}
{"id": "lookup-025", "question": "What is a NetworkPolicy?", "golden_answer": "A NetworkPolicy specifies how groups of Pods are allowed to communicate with each other and with other network endpoints. It uses label selectors to identify Pods and rules to specify allowed traffic. By default Pods are non-isolated and accept traffic from any source; once a NetworkPolicy selects a Pod, only allowed connections are permitted.", "expected_source_files": ["content/en/docs/concepts/services-networking/network-policies.md"], "type": "lookup"}

# ---- MULTI-HOP (second batch) ----
{"id": "multihop-008", "question": "How do init containers affect Pod startup?", "golden_answer": "Init containers run sequentially to completion before any app containers in the Pod start. If an init container fails, the kubelet restarts it (subject to the Pod's restartPolicy) until it succeeds. The Pod stays in Pending or Init state until all init containers complete; only then do the app containers begin. This sequential gating lets you enforce preconditions like waiting for a dependency service before serving traffic.", "expected_source_files": ["content/en/docs/concepts/workloads/pods/init-containers.md", "content/en/docs/concepts/workloads/pods/pod-lifecycle.md"], "type": "multi_hop"}
{"id": "multihop-009", "question": "What's the difference between a Deployment and a StatefulSet, and when would you pick each?", "golden_answer": "A Deployment manages stateless, interchangeable Pods — any Pod can replace any other. A StatefulSet manages stateful Pods with stable identity and storage — each Pod has a persistent hostname (e.g., db-0, db-1) and is reattached to the same PersistentVolume on restart. Use a Deployment for stateless services like web servers and APIs; use a StatefulSet for databases, message queues, and other workloads that need stable network identity or persistent per-Pod storage.", "expected_source_files": ["content/en/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/deployment.md", "content/en/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/statefulset.md"], "type": "multi_hop"}
{"id": "multihop-010", "question": "How does the controller manager keep ReplicaSets at the desired replica count?", "golden_answer": "The kube-controller-manager runs a ReplicaSet controller that watches Pods and ReplicaSet objects via the API server. When the number of Ready Pods matching a ReplicaSet's selector differs from the desired replica count, the controller creates or deletes Pods to converge. Combined with a Deployment, this loop is what makes scaling, self-healing, and rolling updates automatic.", "expected_source_files": ["content/en/docs/concepts/overview/components.md", "content/en/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/replicaset.md"], "type": "multi_hop"}
{"id": "multihop-011", "question": "How do ConfigMaps and Secrets differ in their use cases?", "golden_answer": "ConfigMaps store non-confidential configuration data (URLs, feature flags, file paths); Secrets store sensitive data (passwords, tokens, TLS keys). Both can be mounted as files or exposed as environment variables in a Pod. Secrets are stored differently — base64-encoded in etcd and with optional encryption at rest — and Kubernetes provides built-in Secret types (e.g., dockerconfigjson, tls) that ConfigMaps don't.", "expected_source_files": ["content/en/docs/concepts/configuration/configmap.md", "content/en/docs/concepts/configuration/secret.md"], "type": "multi_hop"}
{"id": "multihop-012", "question": "When a Node becomes NotReady, what happens to the Pods running on it?", "golden_answer": "After a Node has been NotReady for a configurable grace period (controlled by tolerationSeconds on node.kubernetes.io/not-ready and node.kubernetes.io/unreachable taints), the Node controller evicts the Pods. For controlled workloads like Deployments and StatefulSets, the controller then creates replacement Pods on other Nodes. Pods that tolerate the not-ready/unreachable taints can remain on the affected Node.", "expected_source_files": ["content/en/docs/concepts/architecture/nodes.md", "content/en/docs/concepts/scheduling-eviction/taint-and-toleration.md"], "type": "multi_hop"}
{"id": "multihop-013", "question": "How does a Deployment achieve high availability for a stateless web service?", "golden_answer": "A Deployment maintains a stable number of Pod replicas via its underlying ReplicaSet. Combined with a Service whose selector matches the Deployment's Pod labels, traffic is load-balanced across all Ready Pods, identified by their readiness probes. When a Pod fails, the ReplicaSet controller creates a replacement; when readiness checks fail, the Service stops sending traffic to that Pod. The combination of replication, health-checking, and Service-based routing provides high availability.", "expected_source_files": ["content/en/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/deployment.md", "content/en/docs/concepts/services-networking/service.md", "content/en/docs/concepts/workloads/pods/pod-lifecycle.md"], "type": "multi_hop"}
{"id": "multihop-014", "question": "What's the difference between a Job and a CronJob, and how do they relate?", "golden_answer": "A Job runs a Pod (or set of Pods) to completion exactly once. A CronJob creates Jobs on a recurring schedule defined in Cron syntax. The CronJob controller creates a new Job object for each scheduled execution; each of those Jobs then manages its own Pods. Use a Job for one-off batch work; use a CronJob for periodic tasks like backups or report generation.", "expected_source_files": ["content/en/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/job.md", "content/en/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/cron-jobs.md"], "type": "multi_hop"}
{"id": "multihop-015", "question": "How does a NetworkPolicy interact with Service traffic?", "golden_answer": "A NetworkPolicy filters Pod-level network traffic — it permits or denies connections to the Pods it selects, based on source labels, namespaces, or IP blocks. Service traffic flows through this filter: even though a Service exposes the Pods, an ingress NetworkPolicy on those Pods can block clients that aren't allowed by the policy. Without a NetworkPolicy selecting a Pod, all traffic to it is allowed by default.", "expected_source_files": ["content/en/docs/concepts/services-networking/network-policies.md", "content/en/docs/concepts/services-networking/service.md"], "type": "multi_hop"}

